{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 { Jorden often plays very creative and tries all kind of funny things in the openings. However, for this game he chooses a more principal variation with a universal plan that we will discuss soon as the game progresses. } 6... e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3 Be6 9. Qd2 h5 { Giri follows his own Najdorf course. Nowadays, this has become the main way of playing for Black against the English Attack. } 10. O-O-O { Playing in the old fashioned way. This move took a secondary role, once it became clear that, with h7-h5 played, White has no kingside attack, so why castle long after all. However, Jorden comes with a fresh plan in mind. } (10. Nd5 { is regarded as the main line when Giri's theory goes } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bf5 { with plenty of more theory ahead. }) 10... Nbd7 11. Kb1 Qc7 { Besides this move, Black has two important options. } (11... b5 { is active but the drawback is the weakening of the c6-square. However, the dynamics prove that it is perfectly playable. } 12. Nd5 Bxd5 13. exd5 Nb6 14. Bxb6 Qxb6 15. Na5 Rc8 { when Black intends to meet } 16. Nc6 { with } 16... Nxd5) (11... Rc8 { perhaps this is the most flexible choice. Black keeps the options of ...Qc7 and ...b5 for another time. In case, now, White wants to play as in the game } 12. a3 b5 13. Nc1 { Black has the option of } 13... Nb6 { securing control of the vital d5-square. }) 12. a3!? { The start of a highly interesting plan. } 12... Rc8 { It is tough to be a critic of this move, but it feels too slow. Essentially, it doesn't do anything meaningful, allowing White to just continue with his plan. } (12... b5 { was better. Now } 13. Nd5 { is the only critical try to punish 12...b5 but Black should be alright after } (13. Nc1 { is too slow because Black can play } 13... Nb6) 13... Nxd5 14. exd5 Bf5) 13. Nc1 { A new position in the Najdorf arises after only 13 moves. Who would have thought this was possible in 2026! } 13... O-O { When it comes to the Najdorf Sicilian, Giri is king. But for some reason in this game, he was very hesitant to play the natural move ...b7-b5 to start counterplay on the queenside. } (13... b5 14. N1a2 Qb7 { was very interesting. Now } 15. Nb4? { runs into } 15... a5 16. Nbd5 b4! 17. Nb5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Bf5 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 bxa3 { followed by castle when Black has an excellent game. }) 14. N1a2 b5 { Finally, but arrives one tempo late. } 15. Nb4 Qb7 16. Ncd5 { We see the difference. White arrives on the square d5 before Black can play a6-a5. } 16... Nxd5 { Trying to solve the problems in a forceful way, but also exchanging the so-called superfluous knight. Black had a good alternative here too. } (16... Bd8!? 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6! { This is what is easy to miss, the d6 pawn is poisonous. } 18. Qxd6?! (18. Nd5 Bd8! { looks fine, Black will eventually play Nd7-f6 or f7-f5 with enough active play. }) 18... Nc5!! { threatening ...Rfd8. } 19. Qd2 Rfd8 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 Na4! { and Black has a very promising game. }) 17. exd5 Bf5 18. Rg1 Nb8 { Preparing to play a6-a5. } 19. g4 hxg4 20. fxg4 Bg6? { Surprisingly, this is a mistake which went by unpunished. } 21. Bd3 { White's idea all along, but Jorden missed an opportunity to take over the initiative. } (21. h4!! a5 (21... Bxh4 22. Rh1 { looks extremely dangerous. }) 22. h5! Be4 (22... Bh7 23. g5! { is the point. } 23... axb4 24. g6) 23. Bd3! { with the advantage. The pawns on the kingside look very dangerous and ready to tear the black king apart. } 23... Bxd3 24. Nxd3 Qxd5 25. g5! { Followed by g6 and h6. }) 21... Bxd3 22. Qxd3 $14 { The result of the opening is good for White. Black's position is very delicate, no active play and many key squares to defend. The problems can surge on both flanks. Although the engine claims that the position is equal, it looks difficult in practice. Giri defended well for a while. } 22... a5! 23. Na2 b4 24. a4 Qa6! { It is essential to seek for the exchange of queens. } 25. Qxa6 Nxa6 26. Nc1 Bd8 27. Nb3 Nb8 28. Nd2 Nd7 29. Ne4 Be7 30. g5 f5 { A thematic move to shake off the pressure on the kingside and eliminate the g-pawn, but it also has its drawbacks. In search for activity, Black also opens the g-file for the g1-rook and, most importantly, the square g5 is now free for the white pieces, so the trade off is not exactly clear. } (30... Rc4! 31. Nd2 (31. Rg4 { is met with } 31... Rfc8) 31... Rh4 32. Rg2 Rc8 { when he can only be better. }) 31. gxf6 Nxf6 32. Ng5 Ne8!! { Move after move, Giri plays with milimetric precision, but the clock is ticking down and the problems don't go away. Black defends g7 in advance. } 33. Ne6 Rf3 34. Bb6 Ra8 35. Rd3 Rxd3 36. cxd3 Ra6 37. Be3 Ra8? { This is the point when Giri, after a monumental defensive play, lost the game in one move. } (37... b3! { was needed, to stop the white king from coming out. Surely there is plenty of game left, but Black can defend. For instance } 38. Bd2 Kf7 39. Rc1 Nf6 40. Nc7 Ra7 41. Rc6 Rb7 42. Nb5 Nxd5 43. Nxd6+ Bxd6 44. Rxd6 Nb6 45. Bxa5 Nxa4 { This is a non-forced variation, but it serves as an example of how the game could be. }) 38. Ka2! $18 { Turns out Black is lost, all the pieces are paralyzed defending weaknesses. } 38... Kf7 39. Kb3 Rb8 40. Rg2 Bf6 41. Rf2 Kg6 42. Rf3 Rb7 43. Rh3 { One of the problems Black has, is that the knight cannot get back into the game. } 43... Be7 (43... Nc7 44. Nxc7 Rxc7 45. Bb6 $18) 44. Kc4 Bf6 45. Rh8 Nc7 46. Nxc7 (46. Rc8 { would also win } 46... Nxe6 47. dxe6 Kf5 48. Kd5) 46... Rxc7+ 47. Kb3 e4 48. dxe4 Re7 49. Bb6 Rxe4 50. Bxa5 Re2 51. Bxb4 Rxb2+ 52. Kc4 Be5 53. a5 Bxh2 54. Bc3 Ra2 55. Kb3 Rg2 56. a6 Bg1 57. Rd8 Kf5 58. Rxd6 Ke4 59. Kc4 g5 60. Re6+ Kf3 61. d6 Rg4+ 62. Kd5 Ba7 63. d7 Rg1 64. Re1 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


