{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. c4 { White decides to transpose to the symmetrical English. } (4. O-O { would lead to positions of the reversed King's Indian after } 4... e5! 5. d3 d5) 4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 { Moving the knight away from the X-ray of the bishop on g2. Black wants to play with e7-e5 next and setup a Maróczy Bind, typical against the Accelerated Dragon Sicilian, but here with reversed colours. } (6... g6 { is a sound alternative, in the spirit of the Grünfeld Defense. }) (6... e5? { would be a blunder because } 7. Nxe5! $18 { . This explains the need for 6...Nc7. }) 7. O-O e5 8. a3 { This has been played by Hans himself as White, but also many other greats of the game like Magnus Carlsen and Anish Giri. The idea is to play b2-b4 and remove the c5-pawn from the center, while opening some lines on the queenside. Typical breaks in the Sicilian structure. } (8. d3 { as seen in a very recent game, also by Hans. } 8... Be7 9. Nd2 Bd7 10. Nc4 f6 11. f4 b5 12. Ne3 O-O $13 { 0-1 Nihal,S (2716)-Niemann,H (2725) Tata Steel India Blitz Kolkata IND 2026 (14.1) }) 8... Rb8! { A nice prophylactic move against White's plan. } (8... Be7?! { is now met with } 9. b4! cxb4 10. axb4 { and Black cannot grab the pawn. For example: } 10... Bxb4 11. Nxe5! Nxe5 12. Qa4+ Nc6 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qxb4 $18) 9. d3 (9. Rb1 { Black would continue with } 9... Be7 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 b5 { stopping White from pushing the pawn further. }) (9. b3 { is a possibility, simply trying to develop the pieces. } 9... Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Rc1 $13) (9. e3?! Be7 10. d4 { doesn't fully work. } 10... exd4 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Ne2 d3 13. Nf4 Bf5 { White is simply a pawn down. }) 9... Be7 10. Nd2 (10. Be3 { is a natural development. } 10... O-O 11. Rc1 { However, Black remains very solid after } 11... Bd7! { intending to meet } 12. Ne4 { with } 12... b6) 10... Bd7 { It is not clear that White was threatening Bxc6 right away, but this move makes sense because Black would like to play b7-b5 and grab space on the queenside at some point. } (10... O-O { was definitely possible. } 11. Nc4 Be6 12. Bxc6 Bxc4! 13. Bg2 Be6) 11. Nc4 f6 (11... O-O { loses a pawn. } 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Nxe5) 12. f4?! { This is the right idea, but it comes too soon. White should have prevented Black's play first and then go along with his own plan. } (12. a4 { Moving a3-a4 after playing a2-a3 may seem weird, but White can afford it since Black still needs to castle to finish his development. It was necessary to prevent Black from expanding on the queenside before starting any activity in the center. } 12... O-O 13. f4 { The position is tense and with chances for both sides. A possible continuation is } 13... exf4 14. Bxf4 g5! 15. Bxc7 Qxc7 16. Nd5 Qd8 17. e4 Be6 { with complicated play. }) 12... b5! 13. Ne3 O-O 14. f5? { Now, this is the first serious mistake. Releasing the tension in the center gives Black a free hand to play on the queenside. Simply, he controls the center and has more space in that flank, while White's prospects of an attack against the king are unrealistic. } (14. fxe5 { was more prudent, keeping the position open. } 14... Nxe5 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Rxf5 { White at least gets the bishop pair, doesn't mean much, but his position is fine. }) 14... Nd4! 15. g4 Kh8!! { This is a high level move. Before starting the attack, Hans puts his king to safety, away from the a2-g8 diagonal. There are no forced reasons, just great understanding. } 16. Bd2 Be8 { Another nice little move, bringing the bishop to a better diagonal where it can attack the weak square b3. } 17. Ne4 Bf7 18. Bc3? { The second serious mistake by White. The bishop doesn't do anything on c3 and is exposed to get hit by ...b5-b4. } (18. Rc1! { keeping the tension when Black's best response is 18...Na6. The direct } 18... Nb3 { leads nowhere after } 19. Rc3 Nxd2 20. Qxd2) 18... b4 $17 { Now the Hans show begins. } 19. axb4 cxb4 20. Bd2 Bb3 21. Qe1 Ncb5 22. Rc1 (22. Bxb4? Bxb4 23. Qxb4 Nxe2+ 24. Kh1 Qxd3 $19 { The whole position falls apart. }) 22... Bg8 { Making room for the knight now. } 23. Rd1 a5 24. Kh1 Nb3 (24... Nd6 { was somewhat stronger and it also makes sense. Black removes White's strongest knight and, in the end, he has the winning card of 2 pawns vs 1 on the queenside. } 25. Nxd6 Qxd6 26. Nc4 Qc7 $19) 25. Nc4 Nxd2 26. Rxd2 b3 27. Qg3 a4 28. g5 { This arrives very late, but there is nothing else White could do. } 28... a3! { Not wasting any time. } 29. e3 fxg5 30. Nxe5 Rb6 { Once again, it is fantastic to see how in many moments Hans applies prophylactic thinking to stop any tricks. Also, the rook is great on b6 and can switch to the kingside if needed. } 31. bxa3 Nxa3 32. Rb2 Qe8 33. d4 Nc4 34. Rbb1 b2 35. Rf2 Qc8 36. Rc2 Nxe5!! { Every great strategy ends up with a tactical blow and this is it. A superb move, sacrificing the queen to win the game. } 37. Rxc8 Rxc8 38. Nc5 { Temporarily blocking the c-file but this won't last. } (38. dxe5 Rc1+ { is the point. }) 38... Bxc5 39. Be4 Nc4 40. dxc5 Rxc5 41. Qf2 Nd6 42. Bc2 Bd5+ (42... Ba2 { would also win, but Hans' move is even stronger. } 43. Rd1 Rxc2! 44. Qxc2 b1=Q 45. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 46. Kg2 Bd5+ 47. Kf2 Ne4+ 48. Ke2 Rb8 $19) 43. Kg1 Ne4 44. Qe2 Nc3 45. Qd3 Nxb1 46. f6 Rxc2 47. Qxd5 gxf6 48. Qd8+ Kg7 49. Qe7+ Kg6 50. Qe8+ Kf5 51. Qd7+ Ke4 52. Qd4+ Kf3 53. Qd1+ Kxe3 54. Qxc2 Nd2 55. Qc5+ Ke2 { A great show of force by Hans, winning a huge point with the black pieces. Exquisite positional play. } 0-1


