{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

The Tata Steel Challengers offers young prodigies, Dutch players, and elite female players a chance to compete in a fantastic field with excellent conditions. Carissa Yip, a strong young female player who is only 23 years old, has had a great tournament so far. After the fifth round, she has scored 3.5 points and is demonstrating fantastic fighting spirit and precise play. In her recent game, she adopted a very energetic and brave attacking style, which I truly admire. Her opponent was a highly skilled Dutch Grandmaster who had represented his country in numerous major events and won many individual tournaments. }
1. e4 {  } 1... c5 2. c3 { The Alapin Variation is a popular choice against the Sicilian Defense these days. } 2... Nf6 { I believe this is the most logical move, which is of course the main line (along with 2...d5). The idea is to provoke e4-e5 and then undermine the center with d7-d6. } (2... d5 { The other big line. }) 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 d6 (4... e6 { We see this move order more often. } 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 { See the game continuation. }) 5. d4 (5. Bc4 { The other significant move has been played thousands of times. } 5... e6 $13) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 e6 7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { White aims to maintain the strong central pawn on e5. The battery of the white queen and light-squared bishop is rather typical. } 9... a6!? { Played instantly, so it was still Max's preparation. The idea is that in some lines, Black can play b7-b5; also, the pawn covers the b5 square. } (9... Nc6 { This move has been played most often and is critical to this variation. White has various setups, but Max has chosen a rare move. }) 10. Nc3! { The most natural reply. } (10. Rd1 b5 11. Bxd5 exd5 12. Nc3 Be6 $132 { [%cal Gb8c6,Ga8c8] }) 10... dxe5 11. Nxe5! { A principal move. White aims for an isolated pawn structure, which is rather typical in the Alapin variation. } (11. dxe5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nd7! $132 { [%cal Gd7c5] }) 11... Nc6! 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Rd1 a5! { Both players are making very natural moves. Both sides have weaknesses and strengths; I would say the position is rather balanced. } 14. Na4! { It is important to stop a5-a4, and the knight is also controlling the c5 square. } 14... Bd6 15. Nc5 { The first critical position arises. Black must decide where to move the bishop after ♘e4. } (15. b3!? $14 { Another logical move. Preparing ♗b2 gives White a slight advantage. }) 15... Re8?! { Played after more than 20 minutes of thought, I believe this is an imprecise decision, as the bishop would be more dangerous on the b8-h2 diagonal. } (15... e5! 16. Ne4 Bb8! { Preparing ♛c7. } 17. dxe5 (17. Bg5 Qc7 $36) 17... Bxe5 18. Qh5 Qc7 $132) 16. Ne4! Bf8 17. Bg5 Qb6 18. Rac1 { The engine holds well for Black, but White's pieces are standing actively, making it rather hard to defend. } 18... a4?! (18... Ba6! { It's more practical to trade the bishop right away. } 19. b3 h6! 20. Bd2 e5! $132) 19. Qh5!? { A very dangerous position. Black needs to capture on b2 and create some tricks with the queen; however, in a practical game, it seems the queen is almost trapped. Nevertheless, the engine finds some concrete and accurate defenses. } 19... Ba6?! { A creative move played after about 30 minutes of thought. Black had a really nice deflection idea, but after 22.♘f6+, Black's chances are clearly worse. } (19... Qxb2! { Black needed to go for this line. } 20. Rb1 (20. Bxd5? exd5 21. Nf6+ { This simply doesn't work here. } 21... gxf6 22. Bxf6 h6! $19 { White cannot join the attack with her rooks. }) (20. a3 Ra7 21. Rb1 Qc2 22. Bd3 Qa2 23. Bc1 g6! 24. Qf3 Rb7 25. Rxb7 Bxb7 26. h4 Qb3 $132) 20... Qc2 21. Bd3 Qxa2 22. Rd2! (22. Bc1? { This move was intended to be played by Carissa, threatening ♖d2 and trapping the queen, but she missed a strong counterplay, proven by the engine: } 22... Ba6!! { Black gains more than enough material for the queen. } 23. Rb2 Bxd3 24. Rxa2 Bxe4 $19) 22... Qa3 23. Bc4! { [%cal Gd2a2] } 23... g6! 24. Qd1 Bg7 25. Ra2 Qf8! 26. Rxa4 Rxa4 27. Qxa4 h6 28. Bc1 Qe7 $132) 20. Bxd5! Be2! { This is the whole point of Black's 19...♝a6 move. } (20... cxd5? 21. Nf6+! gxf6 22. Bxf6 h6 23. Rc3! $18 { [%cal Gc3g3] }) 21. Qxe2 exd5 22. Nf6+! gxf6 23. Be3! { White's structure is very good now. } 23... f5! 24. Qh5! Qxb2?! { A wrong order. } (24... Bg7! 25. Qxf5 Qxb2 26. Rc2! (26. Rxc6 Qxa2 27. Rc7 Rf8 { Transposing into the game. }) 26... Qb7 27. Rdc1 $14) 25. Rxc6! $16 Bg7 26. Rc7 Rf8 27. Qxf5 (27. Bh6 Ra6! $132 { A nice resource. }) 27... Qxa2 28. h4! { A powerful and energetic play by the strong female player. } 28... Rab8? { A crucial final mistake. The rook's best position was on e8, countering the bishop on e3. } (28... Rae8?! 29. Rdc1! $16) (28... Qe2! { The only move is to hold the position. The queen is doing a great job on e2. } 29. Rb1 (29. Rdc1 a3 30. Qxd5 Ra6!? $132) 29... Rae8!! (29... a3? { A natural line calculated by Carissa. } 30. Rbb7! a2 31. Rxf7 a1=Q+ 32. Kh2 Kh8 (32... Be5+ 33. dxe5 $18) 33. Qxh7+!! Kxh7 34. Rxg7+ Kh8 35. Rh7+ Kg8 36. Rbg7#) 30. Rbb7 (30. h5 Rxe3! 31. fxe3 Qxe3+ 32. Kh1 Qxd4 $132) (30. Rc3!? Re4! 31. g3 h6! { Covering the g5 square. } (31... Bxd4?? 32. Bxd4 Rxd4 33. Qg5+ Kh8 34. Qf6+ $18) 32. Rc8 $13) 30... Rxe3! 31. Rxf7 { I believe both players have calculated until this moment, and honestly, it appears that White is just winning. However, Black has an excellent drawing resource. } 31... Re7!! { What a wonderful idea! } 32. Rfxe7 (32. Rbxe7? Qxe7! $19) (32. Rxf8+ Bxf8 33. Qg5+ Rg7 34. Qxd5+ Kh8 35. Rxg7 Kxg7! $15) 32... Qd1+! 33. Kh2 Rxf5 34. Rxg7+ Kf8 35. Rgc7 Kg8!) 29. h5! $18 h6 (29... Rb6 30. Rc8 $18 { [%cal Gd1c1] }) 30. Rc6 (30. Bxh6! { The nicest win. } 30... Bxh6 31. Rc6! Bg7 32. h6 $18) 30... Qb3 31. Ra1! Qb5 (31... Rb6 32. Rxb6 Qxb6 33. Rxa4 $18) 32. Rxh6! Rfd8 (32... Bxh6 33. Bxh6 $18) 33. Rh7! Qd7 34. Rxg7+! Kxg7 35. h6+ Kf8 36. Qf6 $18 { White is in a completely winning position due to the vulnerability of the black king. } 36... Qe6 37. Qh8+ Ke7 38. Bg5+ Kd7 39. Bxd8 { 1-0 White wins. } (39. Rxd8 Qg7 $18 { [%cal Gh6h7,Ga1a4] }) 1-0


