{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

The 12-year-old Argentine prodigy is very close to becoming a GM. He needs to achieve his final GM norm in an open tournament, but he cannot accomplish this in the current closed round-robin tournament. As he mentioned in a previous interview, his goal is to win the tournament instead. That’s a positive and competitive attitude! His chess skills are quite mature and of high quality. After round five, he leads the tournament with 4 out of 5 points, along with two other players who have the same score. In this round, he impressively outplayed the experienced and strong Dutch GM, Erwin l'Ami, who has a rating of over 2600. Erwin is not only a strong player, but also an excellent second and a contributor of high-quality chess materials on various sites. }
1. c4!? { The English Opening could be a significant surprise, as Faustino is primarily an 1.e4 player. } 1... e5 2. Nc3 d6 3. Nf3 f5 { Erwin is definitely playing an aggressive, asymmetrical opening. His pawn structure suggests he is aiming for a complicated battle. } 4. d4!? { The most principled move was played after three minutes of thought. } 4... e4! 5. Ng1!? { White's plan is ♗f4 followed by e2-e3. } 5... Nf6 6. Bf4 Nh5!? { Black is exploiting the fact that the bishop has no retreat square on h2, but it also has the drawback of being on the edge at h5. This idea is often seen in the London System. } (6... Be7 { Most common move. } 7. e3 O-O 8. h4!? $14 { With the idea that the bishop retreats from f4, then ♘f4 is possible, with a pleasant setup. }) 7. Bd2 (7. Nh3!? $14 { is quite clever as well. } { [%cal Ge2e3,Gf1e2] }) 7... g6 (7... Nf6 { More solid, followed by ♝e7, 0-0. } 8. e3 Be7 9. Nh3 O-O 10. Be2 c6 11. O-O Na6 { With a very dynamic fighting position, White certainly has some advantage. } 12. d5!? $14) 8. e3 Bg7?! { We often see this structure in the Dutch Leningrad variation, but it can be quite dangerous; White may opt for an aggressive setup on the kingside. } (8... Nd7 9. Be2 Ndf6!? { Rather orthodox, but very clever at the same time. The black knights are doing a great job holding the position on the kingside. } 10. Nh3 (10. h3!? $14 { [%cal Gg2g4] }) 10... Bh6!? $132 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gf6g4] }) 9. Nh3?! { It’s logical, but not so energetic as the ♘e2, h2-h4 setup. } (9. Be2! { The most accurate! } 9... Nf6 10. h4! $16 { [%cal Gg1h3,Gh4h5] }) 9... c5? { Black's full power is trying to complicate the battle, but the pawn push significantly weakens the d5 square, which White can exploit very well. } (9... O-O $132 { It would be easier and more flexible to play. Typically, Black has to push the pawn on c6 or play ♞c6; the threat of f5-f4 is also quite critical. }) 10. Be2! Nf6 11. Nf4! Nc6 12. dxc5! { Fixing the pawn structure for White's favour. } 12... dxc5 { This position is very dangerous for Black. The d5 square is weak, and there are many aggressive plans, such as h4-h5. } 13. Ncd5 (13. h4! { I like this move, then playing h4-h5, ♕b3, 0-0-0 with an overwhelming position. } 13... O-O 14. Qb3 $16 { [%cal Ge1c1] }) 13... O-O (13... Nxd5 14. cxd5 Ne5 15. Bc3 Qd6 16. Qb3 $16) 14. Qc2 b6?! (14... Ne5 { More active. } 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. O-O-O Qa6!? 17. a3 Be6 18. Bc3! $16) 15. Bc3 (15. O-O-O! $16 { The most precise. } 15... Nxd5 16. cxd5 Ne5 17. d6!! { An amazing pawn sacrifice. Otherwise, the queen would block on d6, and now White can use the d-file more effectively. } 17... Qxd6 18. Bc3 Qe7 19. h4! $16) 15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5?! { It was a natural move, but it was a mistake. White could better utilize the pawn on d5 and the knight on f4, as the ♝ to e6 often poses a significant threat. Additionally, h2-h4 attacks are more dangerous. } (16. cxd5! Ne5 (16... Nd4 17. exd4 cxd4 18. Bb4! d3 19. Qb3 dxe2 20. Bxf8 Bxf8 21. Ne6 $16) 17. h4 Qd6 18. h5! g5 19. h6! { A very nice intermediate move, probably missed by Faustino, when he chose to take on d5 with the knight. } 19... Bh8 (19... Bxh6? 20. Ne6! $18) 20. Ne6! Bxe6 21. dxe6 Nd3+ 22. Bxd3 exd3 23. Rh5!! { What a fantastic checkmate idea! } 23... Qxe6 (23... dxc2 24. Rxg5+ Bg7 25. Rxg7+ Kh8 26. Rg5+ Qd4 27. exd4 $18) 24. Rxg5+ Kf7 25. Qxd3 $18) 16... Bxc3+ 17. Qxc3 Qd6! { Erwin uses his chances, playing for ♛e5. } 18. f4!? { Faustino made a wise decision. He understands that he needs to protect the e5 square. } (18. O-O-O Qe5! $132 { [%cal Gc8e6] }) 18... exf3?! { This significantly helps White's play. } (18... Nb4! { Black should trade the strong knight on d5. } 19. a3 (19. h3!? $36 { Quite a deep engine-type move. The point is to prepare g2-g4. }) 19... Nxd5 20. cxd5 $14 { [%cal Ge1c1] }) 19. Bxf3 Rb8 20. Nf4!! { My favorite move of the game. Faustino cleverly understands that he needs to use his bishop on d5, while the knight stands well on f4, supporting the h4-h5 advance. } 20... Ne5? { A serious mistake has been made. It allows ♗d5+. The knights appear stable on e5, but White can prepare to play e3-e4, which would open up the e-file, and then the knight will become weak. We also need to keep in mind the black king's position and potential threats to it. } (20... Ne7! { A defending but necessary move needs to be played to cover the important d5 square. } 21. h4!? Qf6 22. Qxf6 Rxf6 23. O-O-O $14) 21. Bd5+! Kg7 22. O-O! { Finally, White castled on move 22. The pin on the long diagonal is now a significant issue, and Erwin likely intended to block it with his queen, but let's see what happened then. } (22. O-O-O Qf6!) 22... Qf6? (22... Bd7! { More stubborn. } 23. Rad1 Qe7 24. e4 Rbe8! 25. Rde1 { It seems like we are close to winning, but the engine is still stubbornly resisting. } 25... Kh6! 26. exf5 Rxf5 27. Qe3 Kg7 28. h3!? $18 { [%cal Gg2g4] }) 23. e4! Ng4 24. Qg3! $18 { Of course, with this weak king, White intends to keep the queens on the board. Now, Black's position is simply collapsing. } 24... Bd7 25. Kh1!? Kh8 26. h3 Nh6 27. e5! Qe7 (27... Qxe5?? 28. Nxg6+ hxg6 29. Qxe5+ $18) 28. e6! { The pawn is becoming very annoying. } 28... Be8 29. Qc3+ Kg8 30. Qe5! { A cute centralization move. } 30... Rc8 31. Rf3 g5 32. Rg3! g4 33. Rd1 { White is playing beautifully with all of his pieces and is completely dominating. } 33... Bg6 34. Rgd3 Rcd8 35. Bc6 Rxd3 36. Rxd3 { What an impressive victory for the young star! } { [%cal Gd3d7] } 1-0


