{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 { The King's Indian Defense seems to be back at the highest stage of chess after a period of being relegated to a lower category. It is always a good choice to seek for a complex game and to create winning chances, but the risk is also high. } 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Na6 8. Be3 Bg4!? { The ideas involving ...Bg4 are trending lately, here or on the previous move. Black wants to force White to advance the d-pawn. } 9. d5 { The most principal decision, White should grab space. } (9. dxe5!? { is interesting too, if you want to play a safer game. } 9... Bxf3 (9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxd1 11. Bxd1 Bxd1 12. Raxd1 Nxe4 13. Nxg6! hxg6 14. Nxe4 Rae8 15. Ng3 { White is better. }) 10. Bxf3 dxe5 11. Qb3! { White has two bishops and is ready to fight for control of the d-file. I think his position is easier to play. }) 9... c5?! { A very risky strategic decision. Black blocks the center but at the cost of activity. The knight on a6 now becomes the main problem as it does not have an easy route back into the game, or better said it will cost Black a few tempi. The upside of this move is that it slows down White's potential advance on the queenside. However, I do not think this is great. } (9... Nc5 { had to be played when the game could continue with } 10. Nd2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 a5 $14) 10. a3 Bd7 11. Bg5 { A typical idea. White wants to move his bishop from the square e3 since ...Nf6-g4 is coming. But first, he moves the bishop to g5 to provoke the weakening of Black's kingside structure. } 11... h6 (11... Kh8 { is another idea, perhaps more promising. The plan is to play ...Qe8 followed by ...Ng8 and then start counterplay with f7-f5. }) 12. Bd2 Ne8 13. g3 { All these moves are standard for this pawn structure. Now White wants to have Nf3-h4 available, attacking the g6 pawn in case Black plays ...f7-f5. } 13... Bh3 (13... f5 14. Nh4 { is a disaster for Black and it shows the idea behind 11.Bg5. The weakness of g6 is hard to defend. } 14... Kh7 15. exf5 gxf5 16. Bh5 $18 { Black is busted. }) 14. Re1 Kh7 (14... Nac7 { allows } 15. b4 { but White is in no rush and can do anything really. Black's position is simply hard to play, he needs to wait for a chance to come. }) 15. Bd3!? { I like how JVF treats this position. With absolute calm, now that the black king is moved to h7, the bishop on d3 reminds him that any ideas with f7-f5 will be extremely risky, and what is a King's Indian Defense without the f5 break? } 15... Bg4 16. Kg2 Qd7 17. Qc2!! { A brilliant idea, not fearing any ghosts. White wants to play Nf3-g1 next and kick the bishop out with h2-h3. } 17... Bxf3+? { I believe this was already a depression moment for Black. Seeing that his position was bad, he tries something but there is no way that Aravindh believed this could work. } (17... Nac7 18. Ng1 Qe7 19. h3 Bd7 { and yes, it looks very depressing, but Black can hope for a mistake when White decides to breakthrough. } 20. b4) 18. Kxf3 Qh3 19. Bf1! Qd7 (19... Qxh2 { White plays } 20. Bd3!! { back and uses the h-file now to launch an attack. For example } 20... Qh5+ 21. Kg2 Qg4 22. Rh1 { and the position looks grim for Black. }) 20. Kg2 $18 { Strategically speaking, Black is completely lost. There is no potential counterplay, he has lost his important light square bishop and White has a dream position to prepare pawn breaks to open up the position. } 20... h5 21. Qc1 { Preventing any ...Bg7-h6 ideas. } 21... Nf6 22. Bd3 Ng8 23. Rf1 Rae8 { Black gets ready for the upcoming opening of the position, but it is not up to him. White calls the shots and JVF is not in any rush. } 24. Bc2! { Threatens Bc2-a4. } 24... Re7 25. Qd1 { White improves his pieces. } 25... Qd8 (25... Bh6 { is no longer a problem since White can play } 26. f4) 26. Rb1 Nc7 27. b4! { Playing on both flanks is what the text books say you have to do, when you have a space advantage. } 27... Ne8 28. Bg5!? { More provocation. } 28... f6 (28... Bf6 29. Be3 { and the Black bishop will have to move back at some point. Still, this was preferable. }) 29. Be3 Bh6 30. f4! { Of course, White does not want to trade minor pieces. } 30... b6 31. Qf3 Ng7 32. bxc5 { Well timed. Now that there is no chance for ...dxc5-Nd6, White takes over the b-file. } 32... bxc5 33. f5 Qe8 (33... Bxe3 34. Qxe3 g5 { is not a lockdown as White would now switch to the other flank with } 35. Rb2 { and invade. }) 34. Bg1 Bd2 35. fxg6+ Qxg6 36. Nb5! { Another good move attacking the weakness of d6. } 36... Ne8 37. Qe2 Bg5 38. Kh1 { Another prophylactic move, almost like saying ''make a move''. } (38. Nxd6!! Nxd6 39. Bxc5 { seems to be winning, but honestly, in such positions there is no need for these drastic things. White can just go slowly. }) 38... h4 39. gxh4 Bf4 40. Bf2 Nh6 41. Rg1 Qf7 42. Qf3 Rg8 43. Nc3! { Now the knight is heading to the kingside. The threat is Ne2 next and Ng3 when the collapse is near. } 43... Rb7 44. Ne2 Rxb1 45. Rxb1 Bd2 46. Rd1 Ba5 47. Ng3 f5 { Desperation, but the fate has been decided long time ago. } 48. exf5 Nf6 49. Be3 Rg4 50. Ne4 { A great game. Reminiscent of the old games in the King's Indian Defense by the chess classics. A modern example of how to play against the c5-d6-e5 pawn structure and how to use the space advantage. } 1-0


