1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 { Fedoseev repeats the line which brought him success against Keymer earlier in the tournament, but Gukesh deviates on the next move. } 4... d5 5. Nf3 O-O 6. e3 { A very modest system, but quite a solid approach. White does not look for anything remotely close to the main lines, but instead aims for a standard 1.d4 structure. } 6... b6! { The exclam does not go for the objective strength of the move, but for the choice to fight. Black could equalize with the most natural pawn break 6...c5 but Gukesh's choice leads to a more tense game, showing his ambition. } (6... c5 7. a3 { already forces some exchanges. } 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 { with equal game. }) 7. Be2 (7. a3 { is also possible and Black will take on c3, but in this case he is ahead in development, even if only slightly. Caruana won a nice game in 2023 against Jeffrey Xiong that went } 7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Bb7 9. b3 Nbd7 10. Bb2 c5 $132 { 0-1 Xiong,J (2693)-Caruana,F (2786) ch-USA 2023 Saint Louis USA (3.6) }) 7... Bb7 8. cxd5! { The right moment to take. Once the bishop is on b7, White fixes the pawn structure, forcing Black to put a pawn on d5. } 8... exd5 (8... Nxd5 9. e4 $14 { of course. }) (8... Qxd5 9. O-O $14 { and Black loses tempo with the queen. }) 9. a3! { Again, precision of the highest level. For the untrained eye these moves may not seem anything special, but now is the right time to play them in order to limit Black's plans. } (9. O-O { allows Black to play } 9... Re8 (9... a6 10. a3 Bd6 { is another option, maybe even better. }) 10. a3 { and now } 10... Bf8) 9... Be7 (9... Bd6 10. Nb5! { is the point. }) 10. b4! (10. O-O { would be less precise since Black can play } 10... c5!) 10... Nbd7 11. Rb1 { This is a typical move in these positions. The move serves to stop c7-c5 ideas and White might also play Qc2-b3 at some point, a3-a4 and b4-b5 to play Bc1-a3 later. However, as it turns out, this is too slow since Black has no intention of going c7-c5 at all. } (11. O-O c6 (11... c5?! 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1! { now makes sense and White gets a slight edge playing against the IQP after } 13... Bc6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Bb2 $14) 12. Ne5! { This is the difference. White needs a tempo to put a knight on e5 and block the bishop. } 12... Bd6?! 13. f4 $14) 11... c6 12. O-O Bd6 13. Nh4 (13. Bd3 { would have been more flexible. White can think about the idea of playing e3-e4 but also continue development with Bc1-d2 and Rf1-e1 bringing all the pieces into play. }) 13... Re8 { Prophylaxis against Nh4-f5. } (13... g6 { and respond with } 14. f4 { followed by Nh4-f3 and Nf3-e5. }) 14. Nf5 Bf8 15. f3 (15. Bd2 { Less committal was } 15... g6 16. Ng3 Rc8 { and now White has the choice of } 17. Bd3 { with a tense game. }) 15... g6 16. Ng3 Rc8 17. Bd2 Bg7 18. e4?! { This was the start of all of White's troubles. His position was not ready yet for this pawn break. } (18. a4 { looks like a better approach, just keeping the tension and preventing the idea ...b6-b5 followed by ...Nd7-b6-c4. Then White can continue with Be2-d3 and maybe push the f-pawn. }) 18... c5! { With all his pieces in ideal positions, Gukesh decides to counter-strike in the center. Probably Fedoseev underestimated this move or simply forgot that it was possible. } 19. bxc5 bxc5 { This is the point, Black does not need to defend the bishop on b7. } 20. e5 (20. Rxb7 cxd4 { is horrific. After } 21. Rb3 { Black can simply regain the material on c3 with advantage but also } 21... h5! { threatening h4 is strong. }) 20... cxd4 21. exf6 dxc3 22. Bc1 { Forced. } (22. Bxc3 Bxf6 23. Bxf6 Qxf6 24. Qb2 Qxb2 25. Rxb2 Rc7 { is simply a pawn down. }) 22... Qxf6 23. Rxb7 Nc5 $44 { Black is down a piece for two pawns, but the c-pawn is extremely strong and combined with the poor coordination of the white pieces, it is fair to say that he has enough compensation for the material deficit. } 24. Rb4 (24. Rb1) 24... a5 25. Rb5?! (25. Rb1 { was better because it leaves the square b5 free for the bishop, nuance that is not obvious to comprehend at all at this point. } 25... h5 (25... d4 26. Bd3 Nxd3 27. Qxd3 c2 28. Rb3 Qc6 { is probably best, when there is still everything to play for. }) (25... Ne6 26. Be3 $13 { is also tense, and unclear. }) (25... Red8 26. Bb5 d4 27. Ne4 { and White holds the pawns. For instance } 27... Nxe4 28. Qxe4! (28. fxe4? d3! $19)) 26. Bb5! Red8 27. Rd1 h4 28. Ne2 { This way each white piece has a good square and this allows White to stay alive. However, I must say that the whole thing looks very hard to understand fully. }) 25... h5! $17 { Now the problems are coming to light. Turns out White's pieces are really clumsy. } 26. Rd1 (26. Rxc5 Rxc5 27. Bd3 { was a better defense, aiming for a blockade on the light squares. } 27... a4! 28. Kh1 { The game is unclear and all three results are possible still. }) 26... h4 27. Nh1 (27. Nf1 { is met with } 27... Qe7! { and there is nowhere to put the bishop. } 28. Bd3 Bd4+ 29. Kh1 Nxd3 30. Qxd3 c2 31. Rd2 Qe1 $19) 27... Ne6! { One of Gukesh's greatest traits is his calculation and ability to spot deep ideas. This is an example, with the help of tactics he gets some material back while keeping the pressure on. } 28. Rbxd5 Nd4! 29. R5xd4 Qb6 { Just beautiful, no words. } 30. Kf1 Bxd4 31. a4 { If we look at the material, White is not doing badly, but with the knight on h1 and the queen tied to the c-pawn, his position is quite difficult. However, not yet lost. The move a4 is a good move, securing the square b5. } 31... Red8 32. Bb5 { Too eager to coordinate his pieces, Fedoseev makes a fatal mistake. } (32. Bg5 { was best when } 32... Rd7 { allows the knight to come out } (32... Bf6 { is Black's best but at least after } 33. Bxf6 Qxf6 34. Nf2 { White has some hopes to save the game. }) 33. Nf2! $13 { which is already great news. }) 32... Be3!! { Removing the defender of d2, Black seeks to invade White's position. } 33. Bd3 Bxc1 34. Rxc1 Rd4!? { Simple and strong. If the d-file is blocked, Black will go through the b-file instead. } (34... Qe3 { was great, but Gukesh would need to see a brilliant idea after } 35. Nf2 h3!! 36. gxh3 Qxf3 $19) 35. Nf2 Rb4 36. Nd1 Qd6 (36... h3! 37. gxh3 Qf6 { was even stronger. }) 37. h3 Kg7 38. Nxc3 (38. Ra1 Qe5 { no hopes. There is nothing direct just yet, but White can't move. It is only a matter of time. }) 38... Rb3 39. Qd2 Qb4 40. Bxg6 Rbxc3 41. Bc2 { Fedoseev resigned without waiting for } 41... Rxf3+ $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


