{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

Vasyl Ivanchuk, the renowned Ukrainian Grandmaster, played an impressive game in round 8. With his extensive experience, he has successfully competed multiple times in the Tata Steel Chess Tournament. It’s worth noting that his peak rating was 2787, and he achieved a world ranking of number 2, which is quite remarkable! "Chucky" is indeed an excellent player with a wealth of knowledge. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 { The Najdorf Variation is regarded as one of the best options for Black in the Sicilian Defense. The key point is that Black retains flexibility, with the option to play e7-e6, e7-e5, or g7-g6, which allows for the development of the dark-squared bishop. White has many lines to choose from, and Vasyl has opted for the ever-popular English Attack. } 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3 Be6 9. Qd2 h5 { By far the most trendy line, which is also a logical move. The idea is clear: Black is preventing White from advancing the pawn g2-g4. } 10. a4 { A very rare line. White controls the b5 square; however, it seems like a slow move. Surely, Black can equalize, but this was a great, surprising idea as White gained a significant time advantage in the game. } 10... O-O (10... Nbd7 { This has been played in most of the games. } 11. Be2 Qc7 (11... Rc8 12. a5 $14) 12. O-O O-O $13 { With a typical Najdorf battle. }) 11. Be2 d5 { This pawn break is quite common in the Najdorf, which was played after 20 minutes of thought. However, White was preparing a strong idea against it. It would be better to adopt a standard setup with ...♞bd7 and ...♜c8, which would make the battle more complicated. } (11... Nbd7 12. O-O (12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5 14. O-O Rc8 15. c4 Nf6! $132) 12... Rc8 13. a5 h4!? $132 { [%cal Gf6h5,Gd8c7] }) 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5! (13... Bxd5 14. O-O-O Bc6 15. Qxd8 Bxd8 (15... Rxd8 16. Na5! $36) 16. Nc5! b6 17. Ne4 Bxa4 18. Bc4 $44) 14. Qxd5 Bxd5 15. O-O-O! { After playing a2-a4 and then ♗e2, it seemed quite surprising that White was not opting for a short castle. However, the rook now attacks the bishop on d5 and can effectively utilize the d-file. Additionally, since the queens have been traded, White no longer has to worry about the safety of their king. White was aiming for this position, which can be pretty annoying for Black. Deciding where to move the bishop is difficult. However, capturing on b3 was relatively weak, as White's bishop pair and control of the d-file proved to be quite effective. } 15... Bxb3? { After 30 minutes of thought, Max made a dubious decision. He probably didn't like the bishop's retreat, but that was less problematic. The absence of the light-squared bishop is a significant issue for Black, and he struggles with it throughout the entire game. } (15... Bc6 16. a5 (16. Nc5 Rc8! $132) (16. Na5 Bxa4 17. Nxb7 Rc8! $132) (16. Bc5 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 b6 18. Ne4 Bxa4 { White has some compensation, but no more than that. } 19. Rd6 Bc6 20. Bc4 b5 21. Ba2 Bxe4 22. fxe4 Ra7 $132) 16... Nd7 17. Bd3) (15... Be6 16. Na5! b5! 17. Bd3!? f5! 18. Rhe1 $13 { With a very complicated battle. }) 16. cxb3 h4? (16... Nc6! { Black needs to develop as quickly as possible. } 17. Rd7! Rab8 18. Rhd1 $36 (18. Bb6 Bd8! 19. Bc5 Bg5+! 20. Kb1 Rfd8! $132)) 17. Kb1! $16 { A very useful move. The king is safe on b1; no more checks from g5 or c8 are problematic for White. } 17... Nc6 18. Rd7! { Certainly, the rook stands wonderfully on the 7th rank. } 18... Rab8 { Black is one move away from ♜fd8, where he would happily trade the rooks. However, White is playing a strong, typical prophylactic move. } 19. Bb6! $16 { Covering the important d8 square. } 19... Rfe8 (19... Bd8 20. Bc5! { Surely, White doesn't want to trade the bishops. } 20... Re8 21. Bd6! $18 { Would win a pawn. }) 20. Bc4! { Step by step, White is improving all of his pieces. } 20... Kf8 21. Rhd1 Rec8 22. g3! { After placing all the pieces on their best squares, Chucky is opening a new front against the Black king. } 22... Ke8 23. R7d5 (23. f4! { This would be the most straightforward approach with complete domination. } 23... Nd4 24. Rd5! $18) 23... Bf6 (23... Bd8! { While Black would get some air, his position remains very passive and weak. } 24. Bc5 f6 25. Bf2!? $18) 24. f4! $18 { Yes, correctly; White is opening up the position. } 24... exf4 25. gxf4 Ne7 26. Rd7! Kf8 27. a5! $18 { With full domination. White's position is simply winning. } 27... g6 28. R1d6 (28. Bc7 Ra8 29. Bd6 $18) 28... Kg7 29. Ba7 Ra8 30. Rxb7 Rd8 31. Bc5 Rxd6 32. Bxd6 Re8 33. b4 { Creating a passed pawn on the queenside is decisive. } 33... h3 34. b5 Rc8 35. Bb3 Ng8 36. Rxf7+ Kh6 37. b6 Rd8 38. b7 Rxd6 39. b8=Q Rd2 40. Bc4 Rxh2 41. Qf8+ Kh5 42. Rh7+ Kg4 43. Qc8+ { A very nice positional game played by Ivanchuk showed an interesting and rare line in the Najdorf, demonstrating how effectively he dominated with a bishop pair. } 1-0


