{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

Bibisara Assaubayeva is a 21-year-old chess grandmaster from Kazakhstan. She is a three-time Women's World Blitz Chess Champion and is currently ranked ninth on the FIDE Women's rating list. Her strength as a player is evident, but competing in the Challengers of the Tata Steel Chess Tournament poses a significant challenge for all participants. So far, she has been performing exceptionally well and has achieved a crucial victory against the renowned Dutch grandmaster, Erwin l'Ami. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 { Bibisara likes the Najdorf variation, so her choice in the game was not surprising. } 6. Bg5!? { I have always loved this move, which I consider to be one of the sharpest variations. } 6... e6 { After five minutes of thought, she likely chose a line she has practiced recently. } (6... Nbd7 { The other main move. }) 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4 Qb6 { A fashionable line. } 9. a3!? Nbd7!? { Black intends to first complete the development on the queenside by preparing moves such as ♛c7, b7-b5, ♝b7, and ♜c8. } (9... Qxb2 { This is, of course, a big blunder. } 10. Na4! $18 { And now we understand the 9.a3 point. }) (9... Be7 { The other main move. }) 10. Bf2 Qc7! 11. Qf3 (11. Qe2 { The other critical move. } 11... b5 (11... e5!? 12. O-O-O { A very exciting variation. } 12... exd4 13. Bxd4 Be7 14. e5! dxe5 15. fxe5 O-O 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd5 Qe5 19. Qxe5 Bxe5 20. Ne7+ Kh7 21. Nxc8 Raxc8 22. Be2 $14) 12. O-O-O Bb7 13. g3!? $14 { [%cal Gf1g2,Gh1e1] }) 11... b5 12. O-O-O Rb8! { It's a typical idea. Black aims to use the pawn "hook" on a3 by playing b5-b4. } 13. Bd3?! { A logical developing move, but it was necessary to prevent b5-b4 or play aggressively on the kingside. } (13. Be1!? { A nice profilactic move. } 13... Bb7! (13... b4? 14. axb4 Rxb4 15. Nd5! $16) 14. g4 Nc5 15. Bd3 g6! $132 { With a double-edged position. } { [%cal Gf8g7] }) (13. g4 b4 14. axb4 Rxb4 15. h4 e5! 16. Nb3 Bb7 17. Rh3!? $13) 13... b4! 14. axb4 Rxb4 15. Rhe1 Be7 16. Nd5? { A typical sacrifice in the Sicilian Defence, but it doesn't work here. However, with the last few moves, Erwin has played for this, so it was logical to pursue it. } (16. g4 Bb7 17. Qh3! g6! 18. g5 (18. Na2 Ra4 19. Kb1 h5!? $36) 18... Nh5! $36) 16... exd5 17. exd5 Nb8! { Black must secure the important c6 square with a defensive move. } 18. h3 h5 { She wanted to prevent g2-g4, which is logical too. } (18... O-O { The easiest way to play. } 19. g4 Bb7! { Doing counterplay against the center pawn. } 20. g5 Nxd5 21. gxh6 g6! $19) 19. Re2 Ra4?! (19... O-O { Again, Black could just go for this. } 20. Rde1 Bd8! $19) 20. Kb1?! (20. c4! { Overprotecting the d5 pawn still creates less problems for White. } 20... O-O (20... Ra1+ 21. Bb1! O-O 22. b3! { - 20...0-0 }) 21. b3! Ra1+ 22. Bb1 Bd8! 23. Kb2 Rxb1+! 24. Rxb1 a5 $36) 20... Qa5! 21. Nb3 (21. c4! { This looks very dangerous, but objectively White still needed to go for this because, without the d5 pawn, the position is rather hopeless. } 21... Ra1+ 22. Kc2 Qa4+ 23. b3 Qa2+ 24. Kc3 Qa5+ 25. Kc2 Ra2+ 26. Kb1 Rxe2 27. Qxe2 Kf8!? $17) 21... Qxd5! $19 22. Qg3 Kf8! 23. Rxe7 { White goes all in because his position is simply losing. } 23... Kxe7 24. Re1+ Kf8 25. Qe3 g6 (25... Nc6!? $19) 26. Bxg6 Bf5!? { Black trades the attacking bishop, neutralizing the threats. } (26... fxg6?? { Of course, Black is not going for this. } 27. Qe7+ Kg8 28. Qd8+ Kg7 29. Re7+ $18) 27. Bxf5 Qxf5 $19 28. g4 hxg4 29. hxg4 Qxf4 30. Qe7+ Kg7 31. Be3 Nc6! { A nice intermediate move. } 32. Qc7 Qg3 { Bibisara played a lovely game. She started with an aggressive opening, advancing her b5 pawn to b4, which opened the b-file for her rook and set her up for a queenside attack. Erwin opted for a piece sacrifice, but Bibisara responded by defending accurately and confidently secured her victory. } 0-1


