{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess }
1. e4! { Keymer plays 1.d4 more often, so this was a certainly a small surprise for Arjun. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { With Peter Leko as a coach, nothing else than the Ruy Lopez can be expected! } 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 { The modern way of playing the Ruy. Essentially avoiding the Marshall Gambit. } (6. Re1 { is the classical line. } 6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O { and Black has many options after } 8. c3 { inclduding } 8... d5!) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. Re1 Na5 { Standard play. The knight moves out of the way in order to play c5. } (10... Nb8 { is another way of clearing the c-pawn. However, it does not gain a tempo. }) (10... Re8 { is also an option. }) 11. Bc2 c5 12. Nbd2 Qc7 13. Nf1 Rfe8 14. Ne3 h6? { It is not clear what this move achieves. Not only that, it feels as it weakens the castle and gives White a free move. This is the start of Arjun's trouble. } (14... Bf8 { makes a lot more sense, looking to play d6-d5 at some point or fianchetto the bishop with g7-g6. } 15. Nh2 d5! 16. Qf3 Qd7 17. Nf5 Kh8 { with a tense battle ahead. }) 15. Nh2! { The weakness of the square f5 now becomes evident. Black can never play ...g7-g6 anymore due to the weakness created by having pushed the h-pawn. It is already fair to say that Black is under a lot of pressure. } 15... c4? { Seeking counterplay, but White's queenside is pretty solid. } (15... Bc8 { had to be played. A sign of things not going so well for Black. However, passive defense is possible. } 16. Qf3 Be6 { White is better but a least Black's position does not collapse yet. }) 16. Qf3 { All forces going the kingside. Attack is calling. } 16... cxd3 17. Bxd3 h5 { An unpleasant move to make, but Black was worried about the knight coming to g4. } (17... Bc8 { was still possible. } 18. Nhg4 Nxg4 19. hxg4 Be6 { when his position is still unpleasant but playable. }) 18. Nf5 g6? { Arjun was not in the mood to suffer a long game, so he decides to play direct and face whatever comes next. } (18... Bd8! { was more stubborn. It is not clear yet how White breaks through. The best option seems to be } 19. Bh6! { but Black can respond with the cool } 19... g6 20. Ng7 Rf8 { which looks delicate, but White must play precise. }) 19. Nxe7+! { After this exchange, Black's position is strategically lost. Basically, he has too many weaknesses on the dark squares and it is hard to keep everything together. } 19... Qxe7 20. Bg5 Kg7 21. Rad1! { Improving all the pieces before the storm. } 21... Qe6 22. Bb1 (22. b3 { keeps the knight away but weakens the c-pawn. However, Black can never really take it. } 22... Rac8 23. Qg3 Rxc3 24. Bd2 $18) 22... Rad8 23. Qg3 (23. b3 { as still there, leaving the knight on a5. }) 23... Nc4? (23... d5! { would have given Black reasonable chances to defend. It is kind of strange to try to open the position when the opponent has the bishop pair, but in this case it leads to simplifications which reduce White's attacking potential. } 24. exd5 Rxd5 25. Rxd5 Bxd5 26. Nf3 Bxf3 { More trades! } 27. Qxf3 Nc4 $14 { The knight is coming to d6 and then maybe to f5. White is better, but there is a lot of work to be done for the full point. }) 24. b3! Nb6 25. f4! { The storm is here! } 25... exf4 26. Qxf4 Rd7 27. Qf2! { Gaining time, White attacks the knight, sending it to a worse square. } 27... Nh7 28. Bf4 Nc8 29. Nf3 Kg8 30. Qg3 { Pinning the g-pawn. New ideas like Nd4-f5 floating in the air. } 30... Rde7 31. Nd4 Qf6 32. Nf5 Re6 33. Rf1 h4 (33... Bxe4 { loses to } 34. Bxe4 Rxe4 35. Nh6+ Kg7 36. Bc1 { and f7 falls. }) 34. Qg4 { Keeping the pressure on, without any distractions. } (34. Nxh4 { would be weak and allow Black to get off the hook. } 34... Bxe4) 34... Qxc3 35. Bd2 Qb2 36. Nh6+ Kh8 37. Nxf7+ Kg7 38. Nd8 R6e7 39. Nxb7 Rxb7 40. Be3 Nf6 41. Qxh4 { Brutal game by Keymer, who took advantage of Arjun's adventurous play. } 1-0


