{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 { A slight surprise from Anish Giri who deviates from his usual Catalan. } 4... Be7 { Black opts for the standard Queen's Gambit Declined, but there are many other options too. Erdogmus decided to play solid. } 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 { The most principal move, this central strike offers Black active play. } (6... Nbd7 { is another way of playing the variation. White usually responds with } 7. c5 { with a complex strategic battle. }) (6... b6 { is quite solid. }) 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. a3 { Preventing ideas with ...Nc6-b4. } 9... Qa5 10. Rd1 Be7 { Erdogmus surely smelled that a special preparation was coming and decided to play the main move, instead of the more fashionable 10...h6 which he had played previously. We are still in common theory. } (10... h6 11. Be2 Ne4 12. cxd5 exd5 13. O-O Nxc3 14. bxc3 Rd8 15. a4 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Rxd6 { ½-½ Lashkin,J (2518)-Erdogmus,Y (2604) 24th ch-EUR Indiv 2024 Petrovac MNE (10.24) was equal and ended in a draw. }) 11. Be2 Ne4 (11... dxc4 { does not guarantee equality. After } 12. Bxc4 Bd7 13. O-O Rac8 14. Qe2 { White still has a slight pull thanks to his more active pieces and the potential for e4-e5 gaining more space. }) 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 exd5 { This is an interesting position. White has two weak pawns, one on c3 and the other on a3, while Black has the weak d-pawn. However, the white pieces are somewhat more active and control key squares in the enemy's position. } 14. O-O Bf6 (14... Qxa3 { was also possible but after } 15. Rxd5 { Black needs to be very careful not to lose immediately. For instance the natural } 15... Be6 { leads to disaster after } 16. Ng5! Bxg5 17. Bd6 $18 { . A nice trap a few players have fallen into. }) 15. c4 { Giri decides to get rid of one of his weak pawns. The funny story is that Giri had played all this before. } 15... dxc4 (15... Be6 16. Bg5 dxc4 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Bxc4 Qc5 19. Rc1 Qxc4 20. Qxc4 Bxc4 21. Rxc4 $14 Rfd8 22. Rb1 Rd7 23. g3 a6 24. Kg2 Rad8 25. a4 Re7 26. Rbc1 Rd5 27. Rf4 Kg7 28. Nh4 Re6 29. Nf5+ Kf8 30. g4 Rd7 31. Rb1 Ne7 32. Rd4 Rxd4 33. Nxd4 Re5 34. Rxb7 f5 35. g5 f4 36. exf4 Re4 37. f5 { 1-0 Giri,A (2752)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2700) Rosmalen Calder Cup Elite rapid 2014 (3) }) 16. Bxc4 { The opening is now officially over and we enter the middlegame. } 16... Bf5 { Erdogmus spent too much time on this move, possibly thinking of the consequences later on. The position is quite tricky. The white bishops put severe pressure on Black's position, especially the one on c4 looking at f7. } 17. Qa2 Be4! $146 { Once again, Black spent too much time on this move. Perhaps he was trying to remember all the details of his preparation or perhaps he was finding the best moves over the board. In either case, it seems like a very bad idea to get in time trouble, not to mention in this tournament with the most dangerous sharks of chess. } (17... Bg6 { which is also playable. However, after } 18. Rd7 $14 { 1-0 Makarian,R (2414)-Lobanov,S (2507) Aeroflot Open A 2020 Moscow RUS (7.43) White keeps some annoying pressure. }) 18. Nd2 (18. Rd7 { with } 18... Qh5 { when } 19. Rxb7? { loses the exchange after } (19. Nd2 { loses to } 19... Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Qg4+ 21. Bg3 Qxd7 $19) 19... Nd4!) 18... Bg6 19. Bb3!? { Lovely move with the idea of Nd2-c4 and then Nc4-d6. } 19... Ne5 20. Bd5 Bd3 (20... Nd3 { was a solid option aiming for simplifications. However, after } 21. Bg3 Nb2 22. Nc4 Nxc4 23. Qxc4 Rac8 24. Qb4 { we get an equalish endgame, where White keeps a tiny edge due to the black pawns being potentially weak, but the drawing chances are high. }) 21. Bxe5!? { The start of some interesting complications. Giri decides to sacrifice the exchange. } (21. Rfe1 { was perfectly playable. }) 21... Bxe5 22. Nf3 Bxf1 { Forced. } 23. Nxe5 { In a critical moment, Erdogmus makes the final error affected by time pressure. } 23... Ba6? (23... Bb5! { with the idea of meeting } 24. Nxf7 { with } 24... Be8 $13 { keeping the diagonal e8-h5 under control which helps in the defense. The position is still alive, and White can continue playing with compensation, but there is no forced win. } 25. Ng5+ Kh8 26. Qb1? Bg6! { is the big point. }) 24. Nxf7 $18 { Now Black is lost, he can't parry the threats. For instance Nf7-g5+ and Qb1. } 24... Qc3 25. h4 { White improves his attacking chances taking the square g5. There is no rush, Black can't bring any pieces out without losing material to a discovered check. } (25. Ng5+ Kh8 26. Qb1 { is not yet sufficient since Black can play } 26... g6) 25... g6 (25... Qf6 { would be met with } 26. Rd4 $18 { with the idea of Rf4 next. }) 26. Be6 { Clearing the d-file for the rook. } 26... Rxf7 27. Bxf7+ Kh8 28. Qe6 Bb5 29. Rd4 Qc1+ 30. Kh2 Qc7+ 31. Rf4 Qc3 32. Qe7 { Black resigned as he loses more material. A nice game by Anish who adds his third victory with two rounds to go. } 1-0


