{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus }
1. e4 { In the 9th round, there was an exciting battle between the Dutch players. Eline is a very strong female player, but this tournament isn't going well for her; she seems to be out of shape. Nevertheless, she approaches each round with determination, striving to improve her game. In a complicated matchup, Erwin nicely outplayed his opponent. } 1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 { We see the Najdorf Variation again. Erwin has extensive experience with both colors, and Eline also knows the openings deeply. } 6. Bg5!? e6 7. Qf3 { This is a very fashionable line that I successfully played in my recent tournaments. The main move is, of course, 7.f4, but there are plenty of interesting variations, including the continuation played in this game. While there are fewer resources available than with 7.f4, the challenge is that Black has numerous move orders, and White needs to be familiar with specific responses. } 7... Nbd7 (7... h6! { I believe this is the most challenging move: asking where the bishop wants to go. } 8. Bd2 { A typical retreat in this variation. } 8... Qb6 9. Nb3 Qc7 10. a4!? { And White rather goes for ♗e2, 0-0 here. } 10... Bd7! 11. Be2 Bc6 12. Nd4 Nbd7 13. O-O Ne5 14. Qe3! Bd7 $132 { [%cal Ge5c4] }) 8. O-O-O Qc7! (8... Be7?! { This is a common mistake. } 9. g4! Qc7 10. Bd2!! { I successfully played this strong move a few months ago. The bishop is now out of the way, and White is launching a strong kingside attack. } 10... h6 11. a3! { A strong waiting move. } 11... b5 12. h4! Ne5 13. Qg2 Nexg4 14. Be2 h5 15. f3 Ne5 16. f4 Neg4 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Bb7 19. Bf3! { This is an essential end of the pawn sacrifice. White is nicely dominating. } 19... Nd5 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. Bxd5 exd5 22. Nf5! Rc8 23. Bg5 $16 { I had a very nice position and won convincingly. This victory over a strong Indian IM gave me confidence and ultimately helped me secure first prize at the Arad Open last year. P.Papp-Aakash Sharadchandra, Arad 2025. }) 9. Qg3 (9. Kb1!? { This is a tricky move as White waits for Black to play b7-b5, after which there is a very sharp line. } 9... b5 10. Bxf6!? Nxf6 11. e5 Bb7 12. Ncxb5! axb5 13. Qb3! Bd5? (13... Ne4! 14. Bxb5+ Kd8 15. Qe3! Kc8 16. Rd3! $13 { In the end, the game will likely result in a draw, but both players need to be very well prepared. The strong Russian female player forgot her analysis, and collapsed quickly. }) 14. Bxb5+ Nd7 15. c4! Be4+ 16. Ka1 O-O-O 17. Ba6+ Bb7 18. Nb5! Nc5 19. Qe3 Nxa6? (19... Qb6! 20. Bxb7+ Kxb7 21. exd6 Bxd6 22. b4 Be7!! 23. bxc5 Qxc5 $14) 20. Nxc7 Nxc7 21. Qb6! $18 { Tsolakidou-Shuvalova, Samarkand 2025 }) 9... Be7 10. a3!? { A typical waiting move. } 10... Rb8!? (10... b5 { Erwin didn't want to allow his opponent to make piece sacrifices on b5. } 11. Bxb5?! axb5 12. Ndxb5 Qb7 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Nxd6+ Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Bd7 16. e5 Nd5 17. Rxd5!? exd5 18. Nxd5 Kd8! 19. Qe7+ Kc8 20. Qc5+ Kb8 21. Qd6+ Ka7 22. Qc5+) 11. Bb5!! { Still, Eline goes for the piece sacrifice, but now Erwin is making a precise move. The players played these moves quite fast, so I would assume it's still preparation so far. } 11... h6! (11... axb5? 12. Ndxb5 Qa5 (12... Qc6 13. Nxd6+ Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Qc5 15. Bxf6! Nxf6 16. Rd2 Ra8 17. Qxg7 $18) (12... Qc5 13. b4! Qb6 14. Nxd6+ Kf8 15. e5 $18) 13. b4! Qd8 14. Nxd6+ Bxd6 15. Rxd6 $18 { [%cal Ge4e5] }) 12. Bxf6?! { After 20 minutes of thought, Eline decided to capture on f6. It would be better to retreat to e3 or take on d7, followed by ♗d2. The main point is that White needs her dark-squared bishop. } (12. Be3 axb5 { The next variation is rather computerist, but I give you a chance to see how complex this variation is. } 13. Ndxb5! Qd8 14. Nxd6+ Bxd6 15. Rxd6 O-O 16. Bxh6 Nh5 17. Qg4!? Ndf6 18. Qd1 Qa5 19. Bd2 Qe5 20. Be3! b5 $132) (12. Bxd7+!? Bxd7 13. Bd2 $13 { More positional approach. }) 12... Bxf6 13. Nf5?! { She plays with spirit, sacrificing a piece, but Black has a nice defense, which Erwin found. } (13. Bxd7+! Bxd7 14. Nde2 Ke7! 15. Rd3 Rhd8 16. Rhd1 Bc6 $132) 13... axb5 14. Nxb5 Qc5! 15. Nfxd6+ Kf8! 16. f4 g5!! { An important and necessary move to play. Black has great counterplay against the f4-e5 pawn and can effectively utilize the dark squares and the open g-file. } 17. b4!? { In an attempt to deflect the queen from the strong c5 position, Black now plays another great intermediate move, getting the queen to more places on the 5th rank. } (17. e5 gxf4! $19 { A significant intermediate move. }) (17. fxg5 Qxg5+! $19 { After exchanging queens, Black has a winning advantage due to having more material. }) 17... gxf4! 18. bxc5 (18. Qxf4 Bg5 $19) (18. Qf3 Qe5 $19) 18... fxg3 19. Nxc8 Nxc5! { The material is now equal, but Black's pieces are better coordinated; the dark-squared bishop is particularly strong for Black. } 20. Ncd6 gxh2 21. Rxh2 Ke7! $17 { [%cal Gh8d8] } 22. Rh3? (22. Rh5! { Attacks the c5 knight, and prepares e4-e5. This remains the most resilient choice. } 22... Bg5+! 23. Kb1 f6 24. g3 { Although the bishop on g5 is less active than on the long diagonal, Black still has a comfortable advantage. } 24... Ra8 $15 { [%cal Ga8a6,Ga6b6] }) 22... Rbd8! 23. Rf3 Rhf8! { The key f7 pawn is overprotected, allowing Black to utilize their ♝ on f6 effectively. } 24. c3 Be5! 25. Nc4 Bb8 $19 { The white knights are not finding good squares; however, Black's pieces are greatly dominating. The knight on c5 is strong, and the pawn structure is much better for Black. } 26. Rh1 Rg8! 27. Rhf1 Rg7! 28. Nd4 Nxe4 29. Re1 Rg4! 30. Na5 Rc8 31. Nxb7 Be5 32. Rd3 Bxd4 33. Rxd4 Rxc3+ 34. Kd1 f5! { White's position is just collapsing. Eline needed to resign. It was a fascinating game, typical of Sicilian openings, featuring strong fighting spirit and tactical motifs on both sides. } 0-1


