{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

In the 10th round, the 20-year-old Azerbaijani player won a miniature game against the former Russian GM, who has represented the Spanish team in recent years. The game was full of tactics and featured many unexpected moves. Additionally, it’s worth noting that Aydin is currently leading the Challengers group of the Tata Steel Chess Tournament. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 Be7 (5... h6 { The Moscow variation. }) (5... dxc4 { The Botvinnik variation. }) (5... Nbd7 6. e3 Qa5 { The Cambridge Springs variation. }) 6. e3 h6 { Although it's not very popular, the engine likes it, which is why people started to play it. :) } 7. Bf4!? { White has an aggressive plan in his mind, aiming for g2-g4 to launch an attack. } (7. Bh4 { A more standard square for the bishop } 7... O-O 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9. a3!? { The position is fairly balanced. White has some pressure with more space, but Black is also very solid. } 9... b6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. O-O Rc8 13. Qa4 $14 { Artemiev-Murzin, chess.com 2025 }) 7... Nbd7! { A logical developing move. } (7... O-O { White is eager to begin the attack once Black has castled. } 8. g4! c5! (8... Nxg4? 9. Rg1 $18) 9. g5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Ne4!? 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Rg1 $36 { With some initiative. }) (7... Nh5 { It would be rather premature, as the bishop enjoys being on e5. } 8. Be5! Nd7 9. h3!? Nhf6 (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5! $16 { [%csl Rh5] }) 10. Bh2 $14) 8. Qc2!? Nh5 9. Be5 Nhf6 { Black is satisfied with the repetition, while White aims for a sharp game, opting for queenside castling. } 10. O-O-O!? O-O?! { Castling is a logical move; however, it makes Black's life very difficult due to the kingside storm. It would be better for Black to initiate a quick attack on the queenside instead. } (10... dxc4! 11. Bxc4 b5 12. Bd3 Bb7 $132 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc6c5,Gd8a5] }) 11. Kb1 { Once we play 0-0-0, it is common to play ♔b1. In this position, it's also clever; however, attacking the kingside immediately with g4 would be stronger. } (11. g4! { That is the most powerful move. White did this in the game, too; however, it was even better to do it right away. } 11... Nxe5! 12. Nxe5 Nd7! 13. h4! $40 Nxe5 (13... Bxh4? 14. f4 $18 { [%cal Gg4g5] }) 14. dxe5 b5 { Black probably intended to play this way, but now White has a strong attack. } 15. g5 h5 16. Ne4!? { [%cal Ge4f6] } 16... g6 17. c5!? (17. Nf6+ Kg7 18. Be2! { [%cal Ge2h5] } 18... Rh8! $132) 17... Qa5 18. Nf6+ Kg7 19. Kb1 $36 { With nice initiative. }) 11... Qa5?! (11... dxc4 { Black didn't want to trade his pawn on d5, but it's a strong move. This can be followed by moves such as b7-b5, ♝b7, b5-b4, and c6-c5, in line with Meran's ideas. The challenge in this position is that while Black has made logical attacking moves, it is pretty challenging to determine the quickest way to launch an effective attack. } 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 Bb7 14. Rhg1 b4 15. Na4 c5! $132) 12. g4! dxc4 13. Bxc4 (13. Rg1!! { That would be the strongest way to play. White has a wonderful attack on the kingside. The plan is clear: playing g4-g5 and then taking on g5 with the rook. } 13... b5 (13... Nd5 14. Bxc4 { This just transposing to the game. }) 14. g5 hxg5 15. Rxg5 Ne8 16. Rg3 $18 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gg3h3] }) 13... Nd5?! (13... b5! { The fastest way to launch a counterplay on the queenside. } 14. Be2 b4 15. Bxf6! (15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Ba6! 17. Bxa6 Qxa6 18. Rhg1 c5! $132) 15... Nxf6 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Qd5! 18. Bd3 $16) 14. Ne4?! { While it is a tempting move, the best is again to bring the rook from h1 into the attack. } (14. Nxd5 { Aydin was scared of this, as he mentioned in the post-game interview. He is right; taking the knight is strong, and White has a better position afterward. } 14... exd5 15. Bd3 c5 16. g5 $40) (14. Rhg1! { [%cal Gg1g8] } 14... f6 (14... b5 15. Nxd5!? exd5 16. Bd3 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 $18) (14... Nb4 15. Qe4!? b5 16. Bb3 $18) 15. Bg3!? $16) 14... Nb4! { Aydin was happy to play this, as he felt he complicated the position well.  From that moment on, the players began to play accurately and energetically, discovering many strong attacking moves. } 15. Qc3 b5! 16. Bb3 c5! 17. Bxg7!! { A great idea: White captures the g7 pawn with the bishop to destroy Black's defenders. } 17... c4? { This is a messy position that can easily lead to miscalculations. } (17... Kxg7? 18. d5+ (18. dxc5+ Kg8 19. c6 $18) 18... f6 19. g5!? hxg5 20. Nexg5??) (17... Bb7! 18. d5! { A significant move. White is blocking the b7 ♗ diagonal. } 18... exd5 19. Ng3! Rfe8 20. a3 (20. Bxh6? Bf6! $132) (20. Bh8? f6! $132) 20... d4! 21. Nxd4 (21. exd4 c4! $132) 21... cxd4 22. Qxd4 Qb6 23. axb4 Qxd4 24. Bxd4 Bxh1 25. Rxh1 $16) 18. Bxf8? { White spent only 5 minutes on this move, which was a crucial mistake, as the white dark-squared bishop was the spirit of the position. } (18. d5! { A stylish move! Now we will see the power of the g7 ♗ and c3 ♕. } 18... cxb3 (18... exd5 19. Bxh6 f6 20. g5 $18) 19. a3! Bb7 20. Bxh6! f6 21. g5! Rfc8 22. Qxb3! (22. gxf6?! Rxc3 23. Rhg1+ Kh7! (23... Kf7 24. dxe6+ Kxe6 25. Nd4+ Kd5 26. Nxc3+ $18) 24. Nfg5+ Kg6! (24... Kxh6?? 25. Nf7+ Kh5 26. h4!! $18) 25. fxe7 Rd3! 26. Nf7+ Kh5! 27. Rg5+ Kh4 28. Rdg1 Rxd5! $13 { What a crazy variation!! }) 22... Bxd5 23. Rxd5! Nxd5 24. gxf6 Bxf6 25. Rg1+ Kf7 26. Qd3! $18 { And Black's king is very weak. }) 18... Bxf8 { Also good; however, the engine shows a nice intermediate move. } (18... Bb7! 19. Bxe7 Bxe4+ 20. Kc1 cxb3 21. Bxb4 Qxa2! $19) 19. a3? (19. g5! { Still a move to survive. } 19... cxb3 20. gxh6 Qxa2+ 21. Kc1 Nd5! (21... Bb7? 22. Rhg1+ Kh7 23. Nfg5+ Kxh6 24. Nxf7+ Kh7 25. Nc5! $18) 22. Rhg1+ Kh8 23. Qd3 f6 (23... Bb7 24. Nfg5! f5 25. Nf7+ Kh7 26. Ned6 $132) 24. Nh4! Qa1+ 25. Kd2 Qxb2+ 26. Ke1 Bb4+ 27. Nd2 Bxd2+ 28. Rxd2 Qa1+ 29. Rd1 Qc3+ 30. Rd2 Qa1+) 19... cxb3 20. axb4?? { The decisive mistake. Now Black wins material by force; his position is simply winning. } (20. Qxb3! { The most resistant move. } 20... Bb7! 21. Nfd2 Bd5 22. Qc3 Nc6!? 23. Qxa5 Nxa5 $17) 20... Qa2+! 21. Kc1 Bb7! 22. Nfd2 (22. Kd2 Bxe4 23. Ra1 Bxb4! $19) 22... Qa1+ 23. Nb1 Bxe4 { It was an entertaining game, but both sides made many mistakes. The middlegame featured opposite-castling kings, creating a very sharp position that required deep, long, and precise calculations. Ultimately, White made the final mistake, and Black won the game. We should note that Daniil is not in good shape in this tournament, so luck also played a role in favor of the young Azerbaijani player. } { [%cal Ga1b1,Ge4h1] } 0-1


