{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess

By far the sensation of the tournament for me was Yagiz Erdogmus. Always playing interesting games and ambitious chess. He was close to beating the World Champion too. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { No surprise here, as Fedoseev was exclusively playing the Petroff against 1.e4. } 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 (6... Nc6 { is the old main line. } 7. O-O Be7) 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Re1 Re8 10. Qb3 Na6 { This is a rare move in this position, but typical in the variation. The knight is out of the way and could jump to b4 and even to c5 in some tactical scenarios. } (10... h6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. bxc3 Qc6 { ½-½ Abdusattorov,N (2768)-Fedoseev,V (2717) 87th Tata Steel Masters Wijk aan Zee NED 2025 (8.3) }) 11. a3 { A reasonable move, just ruling out the possibility of ...Na6-b4. } 11... h6 (11... Bg4 12. Nbd2 Nxd2 13. Bxd2 Bxf3 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Qxb7 Nc7 16. gxf3 Rb8 17. Qxa7 Rxb2 18. c5 Bxh2+ 19. Kxh2 Rxd2 20. Qxc7 Rxd3 21. Re1 Qa8 22. Qd7 Kf8 23. Qe7+ { 1-0 Yuan,Q (2341)-Esipenko,A (2691) Titled Tue 11th Mar Early chess.com INT blitz 2025 (2) }) (11... Bf5 { was interesting, and it could lead to complications after } 12. Qxb7 (12. Be3! dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qd7 14. Nc3 { when White is a tiny bit better only. }) 12... Nac5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qxc6 Rxe1+ 15. Nxe1 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Nxd3) 12. Nbd2 Nf6?! (12... Bf5 { opens for crazy complications. The following line is an example, } 13. Qxb7 Nxd2 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Bxf5 Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Nc7 17. c5 Rb8 18. Qxa7 Qe1+ 19. Kg2 Nb5 20. Qd7 Bxh2 21. Bf4!! Qxa1 22. Bxb8 Qg1+ 23. Kh3 Qf1+ 24. Kg4 g6 25. Bxg6 Qg2+ 26. Bg3 fxg6) 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. c5 $14 { White's position is slightly better. Thanks to a nice space advantage and superior pieces, the knight on a6 is a major problem for Black. } 14... Bc7 15. Nf1 Nb8 16. Ng3 Ne4 17. Nh5! { This is a classy move. White wants to play Bc1-f4 to exchange the bishops and he could have done so with Ne2. However, Nh5 puts pressure on the kingside and offers more possibilities. The impact is immediate, as Fedoseev goes wrong quickly. } 17... Bd8? { This might be the losing mistake. } (17... Nd7 { development is often the answer, of course. } 18. Bf4 Bxf4 19. Nxf4 Ndf6 $14) 18. Bf4! $16 g5? (18... Nd7 { was preferable, but after } 19. Re1 Ndf6 20. Ng3 { it's not easy to see how Black untangles. }) 19. Bc7!! $18 Bxc7 20. Bxe4 Nd7 21. Bf5 Qd8 22. Re1 { In just twenty-two moves, Black is doomed. Nothing can be done. The White pieces dominate the entire board. } 22... Kh8 23. Qe3 { Here comes the kingside assault. } 23... Nf8 24. Ne5 Qe7 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. Qh3 { Seeing the pawn on h6 while gaining tempo against the rook. } 26... Re8 27. Ng3 Kh7 28. Nf5 Qe6 29. Re3 Qf6 30. Nxh6! { The final tactic. } 30... Qxh6 31. Qf5+ Ng6 32. Qxf7+ Qg7 33. Qxe8 Bxe5 34. Rh3+ Nh4 35. dxe5 Kh6 36. g3 Qh7 37. Qe6+ Kh5 38. g4# { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


[Event "Tata Steel Chess 2026 | Masters"]
