[White "Erigaisi Arjun"]
[Black "Abdusattorov, Nodirbek"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2775"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[WhiteFideId "35009192"]
[BlackElo "2751"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[BlackFideId "14204118"]
[Annotator "Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C52"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Evans Gambit, Tartakower Attack"]
[StudyName "Tata Steel Chess 2026 - Annotations"]
[ChapterName "Erigaisi Arjun - Abdusattorov, Nodirbek"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/y4CM41x8/y1iRJ4nx"]

{ Annotated by GM Renier Castellanos - https://lichess.org/@/RenierChess }
1. e4 e5 { Last and decisive game for Abdusattorov, a draw or a victory would secure him the first place. However, when playing with the black pieces at the highest level, the best strategy seems to be to play solid and wait for the opportunity. Fortunately for Nodirbek, his opponent was Arjun Erigaisi, a fighter by nature who does not fear taking risks. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4?! { A rare guest at top-level tournaments. Last game I remember was when Nisipeanu tried to beat Caruana in Dortmund years ago, when he was in a must-win situation to clinch first place, if my memory serves me well. However, the experiment did not work and Caruana won easily. } 4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 Qd7 { Solid and reliable. Very easy to learn as well. Black doesn't want to keep the pawn, but instead is willing to return it and go ahead with the development. } 8. O-O (8. dxe5 Bb6 9. a4 Na5 10. Qa2 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 Ne7 12. Ba3 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Rd1 Qc6 16. Nbd2 Be6 17. Qxc6 Nxc6 18. Bxd6 Rad8 19. Bb4 Rd3 20. a5 Bc7 21. Nf1 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Nxa5 23. Nd4 Nc4 24. Nxe6 Rxe6 25. Rd7 Rc6 26. Ng3 g6 27. Ne2 a5 28. Nd4 axb4 29. Nxc6 b3 30. Rxc7 Nd6 { 0-1 Nisipeanu,L (2654)-Caruana,F (2805) Dortmund SuperGM 43rd 2015 (7) }) 8... Bb6 9. Nbd2 Na5 { Logically, trading the bishop is a good idea as it reduces White's potential for an attack. } 10. Qc2 Nxc4 11. Nxc4 Qc6! { A key move. The idea is to force White to take on b6 quick, not allowing a4-a5 trapping the bishop. } 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Qe6!? { A rare move. Abdusattorov deviates from the most played 14...Qa4. } (14... Qa4 15. Qd3 Nf6 { is also equal, but for some reason Whit scores really well. }) 15. f4 Nf6 16. c4 O-O 17. Bb2 Qe7 18. a4? (18. h3 { is the best move, according to the engine. Hard to explain but it feels like White has to play slowly, trusting the power of his bishop on b2 long-term. } 18... Nd7 { could now be met with } 19. Ng4 Nc5 20. f5 Qxe4 21. Qf2! { when White has a strong intiative. Easy with the engine running, but hard to find over the board. }) 18... Nd7! { Exchanging the strong knight. } 19. Nf3 f6 20. Rfe1 Nc5 { The position seems quiet, but it has to be played on alert mode. Both sides are trying to influence the squares of the colour of their respective bishops. Black is planning to go Bd7-Bc6 while White wants to open the long diagonal. } 21. e5 f5 { Only move. } 22. Nd4 Ne6!! { This is a fantastic move, fighting for the intiative. } 23. Nxf5 { Risky, but passive play is not for Arjun's style. In hindsight, Arjun's opening choice was highly questionable. Black has suffered no pressure, but also White's position is not risk free at all. } (23. Nxe6 Qxe6 { is equal, but I do like Black's position more. The idea of Bd7-Bc6 is strong. }) 23... Qf7 24. Ne3 Nxf4 25. Nd5 Be6! 26. Nxf4? (26. Ra3 { was necessary, threatening Rg3. White doesn't mind losing a pawn in order to open the diagonal for the bishop. } 26... Bxd5 27. cxd5 Qxd5 28. e6! Qc5+ 29. Qxc5 bxc5 30. Bc1 Nd5 { is equal according to the engine, but this is insane for a human. }) 26... Qxf4 27. Rad1 Rad8 (27... Qf5! { seeking to exchange the queens and the white pawns will fall. }) 28. Rxd8? { The downfall continues. With every exchange, White's position feels more fragile. } (28. Bc1 Rxd1 29. Rxd1 Qxe5 30. h3 { gives White better chances of surviving. The pawn on e5 is actually a liability. }) 28... Rxd8 29. Bc1 Qh4 30. Re4 Qe7 31. Re3 Qc5 32. h3 Rd4 { Attacking the weaknesses. } 33. Ba3 Rd1+! { The winning shot. } (33... Qxc4 { is also good. }) 34. Kf2 Rf1+ 35. Kxf1 Qxe3 36. Bb2 Qc5 37. Ke2 Bxc4+ 38. Kd2 Qf2+ 39. Kc3 Qxc2+ 40. Kxc2 Kf7 41. e6+ { This arrives too late, but there is not much else to try. } 41... Kxe6 42. Bxg7 Bf1 43. g3 Bxh3 44. Kc3 Kd5 45. Kb4 Bf1 46. Bf6 c5+ 47. Kb3 b5 48. axb5 Bxb5 49. Be7 Kc6 50. Bf6 Be2 51. Be7 b5 52. Bf6 b4 53. Ka4 Kb6 54. Bd8+ Ka6 55. Kb3 Bd3 { A good game by Abdusattorov to end a fantastic performance and win the tournament. A significant milestone in his career. } 0-1


