{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

When Ivanchuk is in his best form, it presents a significant challenge for his opponents. After a shaky start, Vasyl began to dominate everyone in his path, and the last round highlighted his outstanding performance! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 { The Orthodox Queen's Gambit is a very solid and classical approach to the game. } 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3 { One of the possible lines in the Queen's Gambit Declined was played. } 7... dxc4 { A very rare variation, prepared by "Chuky". He has many interesting ideas in openings, and this is one of them. Black aims to play for c7-c5. } (7... O-O 8. Rc1 c6 9. Bd3 { There are numerous games of this variation. }) 8. Bxc4 c5 9. d5! Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 exd5 11. Bxd5 { White is playing principally, which gives Ivanchuk a chance. If White is aiming for stability, and for example exchanging the queens, it makes it very difficult to create any unbalanced plans. } (11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Bxd5 Ke7 13. e4 Nc6 { Black appears to be very solid here. } 14. Ke2 { [%cal Gh1d1] } 14... Bd7 15. a4 $132 { [%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4] }) 11... Nd7 12. O-O O-O 13. e4 Nb6 14. Re1 Nxd5 15. exd5 Qd6 16. c4 (16. Qd3 { Another approach, which I believe is more practical and easier to manage. } 16... Bd7 17. Ne5 $13 { [%cal Ge1e3,Ga1e1] }) 16... Bd7 17. Qb3 b5!? { A nice dynamic move. } 18. Ne5 { White still doesn't want to accept a drawish simplification. } (18. cxb5 Rab8 19. a4 a6 20. Nd2! axb5 21. axb5 Rxb5 22. Qf3 c4 23. Nxc4 Qxd5) 18... b4!? { Feeling the moment! Vasyl is creating a potentially sharp pawn structure. A less ambitious approach would be the safer 18...a6 move. } (18... a6) 19. Qg3 { Once again, White is attempting to maintain the tension rather than make things simple. } (19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Rad1) 19... a5 20. Re3 a4 21. Rae1?! { But now White is really playing with fire—there are no big chances for a kingside attack, and Black's queenside pawns are becoming dangerous. } (21. Nxd7 Qxd7 22. Rae1 Qf5 $36) 21... Bf5! 22. f4?! (22. Nc6 Qxg3 23. hxg3 Kh7!? $15) 22... Bc2!! $17 { Black is demonstrating his strength on the queenside. } 23. h3 Rfe8 24. Rc1 b3 25. axb3 axb3 26. Rxb3 { White needed to sacrifice the exchange because the b-pawn was very powerful. } 26... Bxb3 27. Qxb3 f6 28. Ng6 Re4 (28... Re2!? { This is more accurate. } 29. Qf3 Raa2! $17) 29. Qg3?! (29. Qf3!? Rae8 30. Qg4 $15 { The queen is rather annoying on g4. }) 29... Qd7! { Prophylaxis against ♕g4. } (29... Rae8 30. Qg4!) 30. Re1 { And now the moment of the game is here! The move, which most spectators would love, proved to be wrong, but the refutation is just fantastic! } 30... Ra3? { The move is beautiful and practically winning; however, objectively, White has a brilliant and safe response. } (30... Rxe1+! 31. Qxe1 Re8 { e .t.c. } 32. Qb1 Qa4! $19) 31. Qh4? { We have a study on the board! The solution is really great. } (31. Qxa3! Rxe1+ 32. Kh2 Qe8 33. d6!! Qxg6 34. d7 Rd1 35. Qa8+ Kh7 { and now fantastic is coming } 36. Qd5!! { What an incredible move! I've never seen such a brilliant saving idea before. } (36. d8=Q? Rxd8 37. Qxd8 Qe4! $19 { Black is winning, and I would not be surprised if Vasyl saw all this before his 30...♕a3 move. } { [%cal Ge4f4,Ge4c4] }) 36... Rxd5 37. cxd5 { White should hold it. } { [%cal Gd7d8] }) 31... Qe8! 32. Rxe4 Qxe4 $19 { Rest is easy. } 33. Qg4 h5 34. Qe6+ Qxe6 35. dxe6 Rc3 36. Kf2 Rxc4 37. Ke3 Rc1 38. Kd3 Rg1 39. Kc4 Rxg2 40. f5 Rxg6! 41. fxg6 Kf8 42. Kxc5 Ke7 43. Kd5 h4 44. Ke4 Kxe6 45. Kf4 f5 46. Kg5 Ke5 47. Kxh4 f4 { Although finishing 1st was close, the 2nd place result was an incredible performance as well. Congratulations to Ivanchuk for his fantastic play and achievement! } 0-1


