{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

It was a very intense battle from the beginning, remaining competitive until the last moments for first place. Andy Woodward (15 years old!) achieved a remarkable victory by winning the Challengers, earning qualification for next year's Masters. His impressive performance of 10 points out of 13 games speaks for itself. He played high-quality chess, and his first-place finish was well-deserved. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 { Erwin plays the fighting Grunfeld opening. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4!? { Quite an aggressive and fighting approach. White is trying to unbalance the position as soon as possible. } 5... dxc4 { The main line. } (5... c6 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Bf4 { This leads to a solid, yet somewhat unexciting position, often referred to as an "Exchange Slav". }) 6. e4 c5 7. d5 b5! 8. h5! Nxh5 { A well-known theory. } (8... O-O 9. hxg6 fxg6! $13 { With many sharp, forcing lines, one must remember to come here. }) 9. Nxb5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Nd7!? { A good move that is a main line in Giri's Grunfeld course. The key idea is that Black aims to control the b-file with the rook as soon as possible. } 11. Bd2 Rb8 { Black is currently a pawn up; however, the pawn structure is quite vulnerable, and the knight on h5 is clearly misplaced. } 12. Rb1 Ba6?! { Black wants to protect the pawn, but this is an inaccuracy, as it simply wastes time. } (12... O-O { Giri recommends this natural move in his Grunfeld course. } 13. Bxc4 (13. Be2 Nhf6 14. O-O Ng4!? $132 { [%csl Re5] }) 13... Qb4! { "Dislodging the bishop from c4 first." - Giri } 14. Bd3 Qb6 { Preparing ♝a6. } 15. O-O Ne5! $132 { We are pleased to exchange the knights and gain control of the e5 square. }) 13. Be2! Qc7 { There are two ways to handle the position: tactically, which is objectively the strongest move, e4-e5, and positionally, which also offers some advantages, as played by Andy. } (13... O-O? 14. e5! { A powerful move. White plans to play g2-g4, targeting the h5 knight. } 14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxh5 $18) 14. Qc1 { The goal is to use the bishop-queen battery on the diagonal. } (14. e5! Bxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. O-O Nhf6 17. Re1 { White has significant compensation for the sacrificed pawns. } 17... O-O 18. Bf3 Qc7 19. Qc1 $16 { [%cal Gd2f4,Gd2g5,Ge1e7] }) 14... Bd4 15. Be3 (15. b4!? { An interesting tactical move, but Andy is attempting a more positional game. } 15... Rxb4 16. Rxb4 Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 cxb4 18. Na4 Bb5 19. Bxb4 Bxa4 20. Qxc4 $44) 15... Bxe3 16. Qxe3 $14 Qf4 17. Kd2! { The white king feels perfectly comfortable in the center, as the queens trade in almost all situations that occur. } 17... Rb6 { One of the critical positions in the game. White must decide under which circumstances he should trade the queens. Andy has been thinking for about 30 minutes in this position. } (17... Qxe3+ 18. Kxe3 Nhf6 19. Nd2! $16 { This is an important move. It attacks the c4 pawn while also avoiding the threat of ♞g4. }) 18. Rh4 (18. g3!? Qxe3+ 19. Kxe3 Nhf6 20. Nd2 Ne5 21. f3 e6! 22. dxe6 Rxe6 23. Na4!? $14) (18. g4!? Qxe3+ 19. Kxe3 Nhf6 20. Nd2! g5 21. f3 O-O 22. Nxc4 Bxc4 23. Bxc4 Ne5 24. Be2 $14) 18... Qxe3+ 19. Kxe3 Nhf6 20. e5 g5! { This is a very nice resource that allows Black to maintain balance. } 21. Nxg5 Nxe5 22. Nge4 Ned7 23. Bxc4 Rg8 (23... Nxe4! 24. Rxe4 f5! { The most accurate variation, although it is pretty hard. } 25. Rh4 Bxc4 26. Rxc4 Rg8 27. g3 Rg4 $132) 24. Bxa6 Rxa6 25. g3 Nxe4 26. Rxe4 $14 { White can hope for a slight advantage now because the king is more active. } 26... Rg5 27. Rd1 Rb6 (27... h5!? { It's an interesting idea. It covers the g4 square, and at some point, ♜h6 is possible, along with a pawn push to h4. } 28. Rd2 Re5 29. Rxe5 Nxe5 30. b3) (27... Re5 28. Rxe5 Nxe5 29. b3) 28. b3! a6 29. Kf3 Rf5+ 30. Kg2 Rb4 { Now we will witness a very rare maneuver by the white rook, escaping from a trade! It did not change the evaluation, but it definitely had a significant psychological impact on the game! } 31. Re2!? (31. f4!? $14) 31... Re5 (31... Nf6! { The most accurate. } 32. Rde1 Rb7 33. d6 e6 34. Re5 Rxe5 35. Rxe5 Rd7! 36. Rxc5 Rxd6) 32. Rc2! { Wow! Very silent, but a really strong move! White is managing to maintain maximum possible tension and will soon be rewarded for this fighting spirit. } 32... Nf6 (32... Rd4!? { Black could simplify the position. } 33. Rxd4 cxd4 34. Nb5 Kf8 35. Nxd4 Rxd5) 33. Na4 Nxd5? { Black did not feel the danger. White's rooks suddenly gained a lot of activity, and it decided the game! } (33... Rxd5! 34. Rxd5 Nxd5 35. Nxc5 Rb6 { would leave just a minimal edge for white. } 36. Nd3 $14) 34. Nxc5! $16 { [%cal Gc5d3] } (34. Rxc5? Rxa4! { A nice shot. } 35. bxa4?! Nf4+ 36. gxf4 Rxc5 $17) 34... Rb6 35. Nd3! { White had just a few minutes on the clock but leaves no chance for Black to survive—very impressive conversion by the tournament winner! } 35... Rg5 36. Rc8+ Kd7 37. Rf8 Rd6 38. Nc5+! Kc7 39. Rc1!? { [%csl Rd6,Rg5][%cal Gc1c7,Gc5e4] } (39. Rxf7 $18 { It would be good enough for sure, but Andy already saw his own way to win the game. }) 39... Nf4+ (39... Kb6 40. Ne4 $18) 40. Kf3! Ng6 41. Ne4+ Kd7 42. Rfc8! Rf5+ 43. Ke3 Rd1 { Desperate, but not saving already. } (43... Rb6!? 44. R1c7+ Ke6 45. Rc6+ Rxc6 46. Rxc6+ Kd7 47. Rxa6 $18) 44. R1c7+ Ke6 45. Rc6+ Kd7 46. Nc5+! Rxc5 47. Rxc5 Ne5 48. Rc1 { White showed great fighting spirit. Even when short on time, Andy tried to keep chances and used Black's first serious mistake very precisely. } 1-0


